stories: The purpose of this paper is to establish a categorization system for multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicons, enabling the application of quantitative and qualitative standards to create a typological classification of lexicographic tools, such as dictionaries, as opposed to platforms and websites. This classification will distinguish between multilingual and plurilingual resources based on their level of prototyping. The paper will also provide detailed descriptions of the various resources, propose parameters and typological frameworks to define and distinguish electronic resources, including multilingual dictionaries and portals, and explore the object of study in multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.

This paper aims to develop a categorization system for electronic lexicons that exist in multiple languages, allowing for the application of quantitative and qualitative standards to classify lexicographic tools like dictionaries, distinguishing them from platforms and websites. The classification will categorize multilingual and plurilingual resources based on their level of development. The paper will also provide detailed descriptions of the resources, propose criteria and frameworks to define and differentiate electronic resources, including multilingual dictionaries and portals, and examine the subject of study in multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.

This study seeks to create a categorization framework for electronic lexicons spanning multiple languages, enabling the evaluation of lexicographic tools like dictionaries using both quantitative and qualitative metrics, distinguishing them from platforms and websites. The classification system will group multilingual and plurilingual resources according to their level of development. In addition, the paper will provide in-depth descriptions of these resources, outline criteria and frameworks to define and distinguish electronic resources, including multilingual dictionaries and portals, and investigate the subject of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.
